bug.short_desc: Editor is not updated after drag&drop a file overwriting

long_desc.thetext:
On a dstore-linux connection, edit file "Martin's file.txt". Enter a line. Keep the editor open.
Copy & paste the file to a Local system. On the local system, edit the file and change it, (add another line) and save.
Drag&Drop the file back to the original location. The "Overwrite/Rename" dialog is shown. Choose "Overwrite".
--> Editor is not refreshed, it still shows the old contents. Even dbl clicking on the file just opens the old (stale) editor. When the editor is closed and dbl click is done on the file, the new contents is shown.
-----------Enter bugs above this line----------- RSE 1.0 Release Test installation : eclipse-platform-3.3M3 RSE install : update-site RSE-complete java.runtime : Sun 1.5.0_08-b03 os.name: : Windows XP 5.1, Service Pack 1 ------------------------------------------------ systemtype : Windows-local, Dstore-win, Dstore-linux targetos : Red Hat Enterprise Linux WS release 4 (Nahant Update 3) targetuname : Linux parser 2.6.9-34.EL #1 i686 athlon i386 GNU/Linux targetvm : Sun Java HotSpot(TM) Client VM (build 1.4.2_12-b03, mixed mode) ------------------------------------------------

I would expect that the editor contents do not change since it's a dirty editor (and there are pending user changes there). At best, a warning could tell the user that an underlying change occured to the file on the host.
If I save the editor at this point, I'm prompted with a conflict dialog, as expected. If instead, I close the editor, then try to reopen via double-click, I'm prompted with whether I want to open with the remote file or the local pending one.
This looks like it works as designed. What would you have changed?

Looks like that's really a dupliate of bug 143462 -- as soon as I drag & drop the modified file over the file belonging to the dirty editor, I'd expect a dialog to pop up and say something like "remote file has changed -- do you want to reload the editor", just like Eclipse is doing this when a file is changed outside eclipse and refresh occurs.
> If instead, I close the editor, then try to reopen via double-click, > I'm prompted with whether I want to open with the remote file or the local > pending one.
I'm not sure this is a good idea. IMHO there should never be differences between "local pending" files and remote files -- they should be the same or this leads to confusion.
*** This bug has been marked as a duplicate of bug 143462 ***

I guess it would make sense to prompt the user for remote vs pending local in the case where the pending local editor is already open.
There are various reasons why the pending local copy may be out of synch with the remote copy. First, someone might edit the file while offline and, at the time of a save, a network connection may be unavailable. Other cases would include conflicts where the user put off resolving anything.

long_desc.thetext: We want to make the Common Navigator the replacement for the Resource Navigator in the Resource Perspective. We need an API constant to call for the id of the Common Navigator to refer to in our code.
Just to clarify, do you mean an API constant for the Project Explorer, which is an instance of a Common Navigator?

There are no exposure points that make sense for this in the common navigator plugins (navigator.ui doesn't define the Project Explorer, so it seems odd to put it there, and navigator.resources doesn't expose any API other than two types for DND). Is this worth creating a new constants interface/type or could we add this to another constants interface in Platform/UI ?

There is no reason you can't use it now - we just want to have a constant rather than hard coding the id of the view.
The resource perspective has been using it since M5.

bug.short_desc: JavaScript Variables not working properly

long_desc.thetext: If I create a global js variable in the initialize and then set its value in the on create of a row to something like aaa += this.getRowData().getColumnValue("QUANTITYORDERED"); and then in the group footer I add a data item with a value of aaa, it produces 2 problems. 1 - it concates as strings althought the column is set to integer. 2 - it doesnt get the last quantity ordered.

Created an attachment (id=53641) example report
attached example with the error

1. the aaa is not intialized, so it is a Object. use a += <int value> will change a to a string. The user should use a = 0 to initialize the variable to number explictly.
2. All data binding expression is evaluated when engine fetch a row. It is before any onCreate of the report item which uses that row. So for the footer, it will use the value just before the last row instead of after the last row.

1 - aaa was initialized as aaa = 0; This was done in the initialize method of the report.
2 - If this is the way it works it is absolutely useless to be able have an onCreate event script set values for a group footer. It is ok to have the data binding expression occur before the onCreate, but the group footer expression should be evaluated after the onCreate of all rows in the group. If it doesnt function this way than the group footer appears totally arbitrary and makes no sense.
What you are saying is that all the rows but one execute the onCreate properly, but we throw the last one away when a group footer is used.

> 2. All data binding expression is evaluated when engine fetch a row. It is > before any onCreate of the report item which uses that row. So for the footer, > it will use the value just before the last row instead of after the last row.
Is the "last row" the data binding row or group footer row? by the time group footer row is evaulated, all detail rows in this group should have been created already, correct? hence aaa += this.getRowData().getColumnValue("QUANTITYORDERED"); should have been evaluated for all the details rows in this group before the group footer row is created?

in the report design, the aaa += this.getRowData().getColumnValue("QUANTITYORDERED") is defined in the onCreate of the ROW ELEMENT, it is evaluated when engine creats the ROW ELEMENT.
The "aaa" is used in the data binding, it is evaluate while fetching the DATA ROW.
Engine will fetch the DATA ROW before create the ROW ELEMENT, so the evaluation sequence is: 1. binding expression. 2. onCreate.

1 - So if I define a variable in the initialize and I use the variable in onCreate on the row, it creates a new instance of the variable?
2 - Ok, but the value was used on the group footer, which should be after the last detail row.

I would like to reopen this issue, since it is not what typical user expected. Even if it is the way it is designed/implemented now, we need to find a solution/enhancement to avoid such confusion from the user's perspective.
the data binding expression and onCreate are executed in two different scopes, we need find new solution to distinguish them. defer to RC0
*** Bug 173879 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***

In BIRT engine design, expression in data binding are evaluated before the report item's onCreate() script are evaluated. For example, if there is a data binding expression of resultsetCol1 = aaa, and a data item in the group footer is using this resultsetCol1, the data item will get the value of "aaa" during the data binding calculation. Since BIRT engine will first calculate the data binding for a report item before calling the onCreate() of this same report item, resultsetcol1 in data binding will be set to aaa's value BEFORE the onCreate() of the report item is called.
The easy of use is that such data binding is created when user enter an expression for a data item automatically. It is not clear to the user that he/she is creating a data binding, instead the UI suggests more like the data report item is being set to a global var, and it has nothing to do with the data binding. Hence the expression for the data item should be evaluated WHEN this data item is being created. However, BIRT engine doesn't know that the expression in the data binding is TIED to this data item, so it should not evaluate it until the data item is being creating. In stead, Engine will try to calculate all the expression first.
Solution to be discussed: Can engine change the data binding calculation sequence to calculate one data row-->generate one table row-->calculate next data row... Open issue for this solution: if there is a chart in the group header that needs all the data rows for the group, DtE needs to prepare all the rows for the chart. But when the chart in the group headers is being created, the detail rows in the group have not been created, so the onCreate() will not be executed. In this case, the databinding expression that uses global var aaa that will be incremented in the onCreate() will be set to a value BEFORE it is incremented by each row()'s onCreate(). And once the dataBinding is evaulated, it will not be evaulated again in the group footer, hence the aaa show up in the footer will not include the increments made in each detail row's onCreate().
Need further investigation in how to address this conflicting requirement on data binding evaluation sequence.
Another possible solution is to allow data item to be set to an expression explicitly, and then a data item is set to an expression, such as using "value-of(aaa)" as the value string of the data item. When the value of a data item has this string, instead of the row(resultsetCol1) string, We will not create a data binding for it. Instead treat it like a text item with a <value-of> "aaa" </> string.
A work around for this paticular report is to use text report item, instead of data item, to show the aaa value. which is a manul way to implement the above solution.

bug.short_desc: Failed to open team repository

long_desc.thetext:
It appears that there is a bug with the Team Member repository. It does not work in a distributed environment.
The PCC-View page for Team Member reports the following error:
Failed to open team repository.
I believe this is caused by the Repository Definition uses a file-path. This cannot be resolved since the path is no longer on the same machine where the server is not localhost. Consequently, the Workbench cannot access the Team Member repository. The Repository Definition for the Team Member is:
<repository-descriptor content-type="http://www.eclipse.org/corona/contentTypes/teamContent" name="TeamMemberRepository" uri="http://www.eclipse.org/corona/repository/CoronaDemoTeamRepository"> <description>Team member repository definition</description> <repository-configurations default-configuration-name="allMembers"> <repository-configuration name="allMembers"> <repository-connection-parameters access-type="http://www.eclipse.org/corona/accessTypes/xml" name="TeamMemberRepositoryConnectionParameters"> <repository-connection-parameter name="file-path" value="${CORONA_CONFIG_HOME}/repositories/CoronaDemoTeamRepository.xml"/> </repository-connection-parameters> </repository-configuration> </repository-configurations> </repository-descriptor>
I think this will cause another problem with collaboration events. If I remember correctly, collaboration events are only published from Workbenches whose user is a member of the Team Member repository. Consequently, collaboration events may only be local to the Workbench and not shared to the Workgroup.
Marcin provided this fix. The Repo Desc is checked if it has a 'uri' connection parameter. If so, than it is used. This will allow the WB client to access the remote XML file.

From my limited knowledge of this area:
The configuration area, as designed, can be shared only on "static" instances of Eclipse where none of the Eclipse instances using the shared config area modifies it while other instances are running.

Interesting bug. This should in theory not happen because the configuration area has a file table structure that should result in "atomic" writes (loosely speaking). Perhaps the -clean code is cavalier about toasting files...

Yes that is what I think is happening here.
- Instance X is in the process of shutting down. It locks the StorageManager and starts to write its cache.
- After instance X has save some of its files, instance Y start with -clean. When launching with -clean we do not try to lock the StorageManager because we are about to delete the configuration which includes the files we use to lock the StorageManager. This means we delete the files instance X just saved
- Instance X finishes saving its cache.
- Instance Y continues starting and finds half a cache available from instance X. This is where the failure occurs.

bug.short_desc: Run on server does not check canModifyModule()

long_desc.thetext:
When selecting run on server on child J2EE module, e.g. web or ejb, the current "run on server" code only uses the module types that are defined on the runtime definition to decide whether the module can run on a server or not. However, the canModifyModule() is not being used. If an existing server happens to only support running EAR module (but support directly running a web module), the server will still shows up in the run on server dialog even if a user selects a web module that doesn't have a parent EAR module.
The current code in RunOnServerActionDelegate.
This problem need to be fixed in WTP 1.5.3.

I'm a little confused - which case are you taking about? The non-UI paths through RunOnServerActionDelegate don't call canModifyModules(), but they do call modifyModules(), which should throw a similar exception if there is a problem. The UI case goes through the add/remove project wizard.
I'm not sure if there is a path that's actually failing in Run on Server, or whether you are expecting that the failure from canModifyModules() is automatically fired from modifyModules() by the framework if someone doesn't call canModifyModules().

When someone is selecting run on server on a web project, the framework should call canModifyModule() to make sure the module can be added to the server to show only the servers that can run that particular module. Just like what the add/remove dialog does. Otherwise, the user will end up seeing the servers that may not support the selected project, then see an error when hitting the finish instead. This looks like an inconsistency in the behaviour on the GUI from the add/remove project dialog.
If the canModifyModule() cannot be called to filter out the modules, e.g. for performance reason, then the framework should still call the canModifyModule() before calling modifyModule() in the run on server case to make sure the module can be added to the server since the check has never been done before.
From the API point of view, we shouldn't rely on the modifyModule() to throw exception on things that has already been checked on canModifyModule(). Otherwise, we are forcing the individual server implementation to call the canModifyModule() check again before doing any of the modifyModule() operation. This will result in forcing the execution of the canModifyModule() twice in certain scenarios, e.g. in the add/remove project scenario for which the framework will call the canModifyModule() before bring up the dialog.
Therefore, I think the fix of this problem should either be calling the canModifyModule() to filter out the servers before bring up the run on server dialog or call the canModifyModule() before executing the modifyModule() in the run on server scenario.

Ok, I understand the issue now. canModifyModules() is actually being called on the second page (modify modules), but it's not called on the first page of the wizard when you're selecting an existing server. It just calls getRootModules() and assumes the root is valid. I will add this check and get it in 1.5.3.
Two notes: 1) There is currently no errors either in the case where getRootModules() returns an empty list. This should never happen according to the API, but to cover mistakes in server adapters it should give an error. Since this part is less critical and involves new translation, I'll only put it in 2.0.
2) The one part I disagree with is your comment about relying on canModifyModules() being called before modifyModule(). This should absolutely be true when talking about WTP server tools, but other clients (e.g. other components, WTP adopter products) could be less thorough or have bugs in their code. It's not too big a leap to assume that some of them 'know' they have a correct module and will try to add it to the server before calling canModifyModules(). To close this hole, some options are:
* Server adapters should call canModifyModules() (or otherwise ensure that the module is ok) from within modifyModules().
* Server core API could spec that it will always call canModifyModules() internally before calling modifyModules(), even if the client already made that call.

Released fix to 1.5.3 and 2.0 M5 builds.
Discussed with Elson, and we decided that modifyModules() should be spec'd to return the same results as canModifyModules() if canModifyModules() failed, and will have to make the (possibly duplicate) call internally. This change (and improved javadoc) released to 2.0M5 builds only.

/** * @return Returns the params. */ public Map getParams() {...} /** * @return Returns the contributorName. */ public String getContributorName() {...} /** * @return Returns the id. */ public String getId() {...}

bug.short_desc: [Webapp] Search result description in external Help window should be hideable

long_desc.thetext:
The Search result description introduced in Eclipse 3.2 usually makes results hard to read, because the first few lines of Help topics are not necessarily relevant to what the user is looking for. We miss the simple list of links in 3.1 Search.
In Dynamic Help, the Search view provides a button to toggle the result description on and off, which is great. Unfortunately, the option is not available in the external Help window Search. Can you please provide one?
If feasible, we would also like to search results to display hit rates, as they did in 3.1.
Many thanks, Denis

About the display of the hit rates, my teams had requested the ability to turn on/off display of the percentage rates in this bugzilla request for enhancement: https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=104899
In the opening of that request for enhancement, we asked for input from the Eclipse community; as you can see from the bugzilla entry URL above, there was not much voiced in favor of display of the percentage rates.
Basically, our consumers did not like to see the percentage hit rates because they got confusing for why a topic had 79% and another got 81%, and to the users, the topics appeared equally valid for that search. We kept having to expend lots of people time to respond to this question, when it was really immaterial.
You will see in the above bugzilla URL that we did request a preference to allow Eclipse consumers to turn on/off the display of the rates as they see fit for their end users. If that is the function that would meet your need, then please open a request for enhancement for a new preference to do that in 3.3.
--Lee Anne

I don't feel too strongly one way or the other, but as a user of internet searches, I personally have no use for hit rate numbers. These numbers seem arbitrary to me. I make a general assumption that the search engine will place the most relevant hits at the top and sort by ascending relevance. Knowing the exact number (and displaying it for each hit) seems less important to me.
What we could do is improve the quality of the description we show by showing the text around the hit instead of the first couple of sentences of the document. We can also duplicate the control we have in the dynamic help view that toggles the description on and off. As for hit rate, the most popular search engines seem to be going away from it.

There are two issues in this bug:
The main problem and the one listed in the description is a request to be able to hide descriptions in the Webapp. This was fixed in 3.3, I'm not sure if there was a bug number to use as a DUPLICATE, so I'll close this as WORKSFORME.
The second issue relates to search hit rates. We don't plan to reintroduce that because we got a lot of negative feedback in the form of "What does that number mean" or "Why does this result have such a low/high score" but it's interesting to find that some users found these useful.

bug.short_desc: Provide a listening mechanism for native dialogs

long_desc.thetext:
The TPTP automated GUI recorder is required to record user's interactions with native dialogs. Currently there is no mechanism available for a recorder to listen on events from such dialogs. An example of a native dialog is the open/save file dialog that appears when users typically click on a browse button.
A listener should be notified of the returned value of the dialog (e.g. the file/folder selected) and whether OK/cancel is selected. This basic fix will greatly help us in providing a solution for the following TPTP enhancement:
https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=124717
I've noticed that this hasn't been triaged. This defect is desperately required by a TPTP component. What is the likelihood of it being fixed in 3.3?
Can you tell me what you are doing now for non-native dialogs?

Ok, it's not clear to me what form this API would take. Do you have a suggestion?
For example, a MessageBox opens and the user can choose one of one to three buttons. How does should this be reported? When a FileDialog opens, the user chooses a file or cancels. Do you need to know the path that was chosen?

In an effort not to make the listeners or events specific to a type of native dialog, the reported events should be similar to what SWT reports. For example in the case of a button selection of a MessageBox, an equivalent SWT.Selection (e.g. Native.Selection) event should be fired with the appropriate attributes.
More importantly, there should be a mechanism in place to be able to play-back these native events. For example, the MessageBox button selection should programmatically be selected if the following events (with the correct attributes) are added to the display event queue:
1) SWT.Selection (corresponds to an SWT button selection that results in opening a MessageBox) 2) Native.Selection (corresponds to an OK button selection of a MessageBox)
